|[[Kent]]<br/><small>{{Coord|51.3203|1.2365|name=All Saints, West Stourmouth}}</small>
|[[File:All Saints, West Stourmouth, Kent - geograph.org.uk - 325441.jpg|100px|alt=A flint church with a red tied roof and a tower at the west end, seen from the southeast]]
| style="text-align:center;"|{{sort|0850|[[Anglo-Saxon England|Anglo-Saxon]]}}
|The oldest fabric in the church is Anglo-Saxon.  The church was altered in the 12th&nbsp;century, but following earthquake damage in 1382 it was rebuilt.  Windows were replaced in the 14th and 15th&nbsp;centuries, and the church was [[Victorian restoration|restored]] in 1845.  It has been redundant since 1979.  The base of a [[rood screen]] is still present inside the church.<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.visitchurches.org.uk/visit/church-listing/all-saints-west-stourmouth.html | title = All Saints' Church, West Stourmouth, Kent| accessdate = 15 October 2016 | publisher = [[Churches Conservation Trust]]}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1203363|desc= Church of All Saints, Stourmouth|accessdate= 28 March 2015|mode=cs2|ps=none|fewer-links=x}}</ref>
