! scope="row"|{{sort|Albury|[[Old St Peter and St Paul's Church, Albury|St&nbsp;Peter and St&nbsp;Paul (old)]]<br/>[[Albury, Surrey|Albury]]}}
|[[Surrey]]<br/><small>{{Coord|51.2200|-0.4790|name=St Peter and St Paul (old), Albury}}</small>
|[[File:The Saxon Church of St Peter and St Paul - geograph.org.uk - 669309.jpg|100px|alt=A stone church seen from the south, showing a transept with a large window, and a tower surmounted by a cupola]]
| style="text-align:center;"|{{sort|1050|11th&nbsp;century}}
|The [[nave]] may date from the [[Anglo-Saxon England|Anglo-Saxon era]], and the lower part of the tower contains pre-[[Norman conquest of England|Conquest]] masonry.  The nave was extended in the 12th&nbsp;century, the [[chancel]] and south [[transept]] were added in the 13th&nbsp;century, followed by the south [[aisle]] in the following century.  During the 19th&nbsp;century the Albury Park estate, in which the church stands, was owned by the banker [[Henry Drummond (1786–1860)|Henry Drummond]].  He replaced the spire on the tower with a [[cupola]], and commissioned [[Augustus Welby Northmore Pugin|A.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;N.&nbsp;Pugin]] to convert the south transept into a [[Morgue|mortuary chapel]].<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.visitchurches.org.uk/visit/church-listing/st-peter-and-st-paul-albury.html | title = Church of St Peter & St Paul, Albury, Surrey | accessdate = 15 October 2016 | publisher = [[Churches Conservation Trust]]}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1294958|desc= The Old Parish Church of St Peter and St Paul, Albury|accessdate= 28 March 2015|mode=cs2|ps=none|fewer-links=x}}</ref>
<ref>{{Citation| url = http://www.alburychurches.org/saxon.html| title = The Saxon Church of St Peter and St Paul| accessdate = 13 May 2011| publisher = The Parish of Albury, Surrey| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110719200659/http://www.alburychurches.org/saxon.html| archivedate = 19 July 2011| df = }}</ref>
