| style="text-align:center;"|{{sort|1050|11th&nbsp;century}}
|[[Norman architecture|Norman]] features in the church include a north window, the [[baptismal font|font]], and a [[piscina]].  Also in the church is the [[alabaster]] tomb of Sir&nbsp;Thomas Fettiplace, who died in 1447, and his wife, Lady Beatrice, who was a member of the Portuguese royal family.  On the walls above the chancel arch are 12th-century paintings and painted texts. Worship ceased in the church in 1870, and its congregation transferred to a new church nearby.<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.visitchurches.org.uk/visit/church-listing/st-thomas-east-shefford.html | title = St Thomas' Church, East Shefford, Berkshire | accessdate = 15 October 2016 | publisher = [[Churches Conservation Trust]]}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1321841|desc= The Old Church, Great Shefford|accessdate= 28 March 2015|mode=cs2|ps=none|fewer-links=x}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url= http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=62706#s3|title= Parishes: East Shefford or Little Shefford |accessdate= 13 May 2011|editor1-last= Page|editor1-first= William|editor1-link=William Henry Page |editor2-last= Ditchfield|editor2-first=P. H.|work= A History of the County of Berkshire|volume = 4|year=1945 |series = [[Victoria County History]] |publisher= University of London & History of Parliament Trust |pages= 234–238}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| last = Baxter| first = Ron| author-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2008| title = St Thomas, East Shefford, Berkshire| publisher = Corpus of Romanesque Sculpture of Great Britain and Ireland| url = http://www.crsbi.ac.uk/resources/fglossary/H43_beading/site/H43_beading/ed-be-eshef.html| accessdate = 13 May 2011| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121009220526/http://www.crsbi.ac.uk/resources/fglossary/H43_beading/site/H43_beading/ed-be-eshef.html| archivedate = 9 October 2012| df = }}</ref>
