|[[File:StPetersChurch.Sandwich.jpg|100px|alt=A stone church with a central tower, red tiled roofs, and a protruding vestry with a Dutch gable]]
| style="text-align:center;"|{{sort|1250|13th&nbsp;century}}
|In 1560 St Peter's became the church for a group of Dutch [[Protestantism|Protestants]].  The tower collapsed in 1661, destroying the south aisle.  The tower was rebuilt, but the south aisle was left ruined and the south [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]] was filled in.  A  [[cupola]] was added to the top of the tower.  In the 1860s the west end was restored after it was damaged in a storm.  Under the [[chancel]] is a [[Vault (architecture)|vaulted]] [[undercroft]] lit by two 13th-century openings, which was probably used as a [[charnel house]].<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.visitchurches.org.uk/visit/church-listing/st-peter-sandwich.html | title = St Peter's Church, Sandwich, Kent | accessdate = 15 October 2016 | publisher = [[Churches Conservation Trust]] | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161019032437/https://www.visitchurches.org.uk/visit/church-listing/st-peter-sandwich.html | archivedate = 19 October 2016 | df =  }}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1343813|desc= Church of St Peter, Sandwich|accessdate= 28 March 2015|mode=cs2|ps=none|fewer-links=x}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| url = http://www.stpeterschurch-sandwich.org.uk/history.htm| title = History| accessdate = 18 May 2011| publisher = St Peter's Church, Sandwich| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120211110520/http://www.stpeterschurch-sandwich.org.uk/history.htm| archivedate = 11 February 2012| df = }}</ref>
