|The church is notable for its wall paintings dating from about 1400.  When they were rediscovered during a [[Victorian restoration|restoration]] in 1849 they had been covered in plaster for 300&nbsp;years.  The paintings were restored in the 1930s and depict, among other subjects, [[Saint George]] and the dragon, and Saints [[Helena (Empress)|Helena]] and [[Saint Eligius|Eligius]].  There is also a [[Doom (painting)|doom painting]] and a [[Pietà]]; these were intended to be a warning against swearing.  The stained glass includes windows designed by A.&nbsp;Gibbs and [[Charles Eamer Kempe|C.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;Kempe]].<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.visitchurches.org.uk/visit/church-listing/st-lawrence-broughton.html | title = St Lawrence's Church, Broughton, Buckinghamshire | accessdate = 15 October 2016 | publisher = [[Churches Conservation Trust]]}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1332313|desc= Church of St Lawrence, Broughton|accessdate= 28 March 2015|mode=cs2|ps=none|fewer-links=x}}</ref>
