{{Orphan|date=December 2011}}
'''Tana ware''' refers to a type of prehistoric [[pottery]] prominent around the [[Lake Tana]] near northwest [[Ethiopia]], and Kaya settlements of the coastal hinterland of Kenya.<ref>[http://collections.si.edu/search/results.jsp?q=record_ID:siris_sil_751249 collections.si]</ref>
The name Tana ware was given because the early discoveries of these types of pottery were along the [[Tana River (Kenya)|Tana River]] in present day Kenya.
==History== The book ''Societies, Religion, and History: Central East Tanzanians and the World They Created, c. 200 BCE to 1800 CE'' asks: "Did a new ethno-linguistic community introduce Tana ware to the region, or did extant EIA Kwale ware makers innovate a new style through a series of transitions that resulted in Tana ware?" The book also comments that "Taking into consideration the marked typological distinctions in Tana ware motifs, even when shared aesthetic influences may be noted, it is more probable that recently arrived NECB speakers manufactured the Tana ware.".<ref>[http://www.wordnik.com/words/Tana wordnik.com]</ref>
In the 5th and 6th centuries, Tana ware began to replace Kwale ware in the [[Usambara]] region.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1i-IBmCeNhUC&pg=PA188&lpg=PA188&dq=Tana+ware&source=bl&ots=qoj21GC-fI&sig=E4QBShVFCx6LX968r3zxA6hnnP4&hl=en&ei=wjjWTrCmEsqViAfPpNVy&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Tana%20ware&f=false Google Books]</ref>
